just_use replay.go

# label: WORKHORSE
# role: domain — server-authoritative state reconstruction from WireActions

Mirror of `elm-port-docs/src/LynRummy/Replay.elm`. Takes a
`WireAction` and applies it to a `(Board, Hand)` state to produce
the next state. Stateless, pure, deterministic.

## Exposed surface

- `type State struct { Board []CardStack; Hand Hand }`
- `InitialState() State` — 6-stack opening board + 15-card
  canned opening hand (matches Elm's Dealer.initialBoard +
  Dealer.openingHand exactly).
- `ApplyAction(action WireAction, state State) State` — applies
  one action; silent no-op on bad references or invalid merges.
- `ReplayActions(actions []WireAction) State` — folds ApplyAction
  over a list from InitialState.

## Behavior contract

Matches the Elm Replay module byte-for-byte in transition
semantics:

- Split, MergeStack, MergeHand, PlaceHand, MoveStack produce
  the expected (Board, Hand) mutations.
- Draw / Discard / CompleteTurn / Undo are no-ops for now
  (turn-logic not modeled). They'll get transitions when turn
  flow lands.
- Out-of-bounds indices and not-in-hand card references are
  silent no-ops — the same contract as the Elm side.

## Positional indices — important

Wire actions carry positional `stack_index` relative to the
board list at emit time. Every mutation (split / merge / place /
move) shifts indices. Callers (human or scripted) that cache
an index across mutations will hit stale references. The Python
client has `find_stack_containing()` for content-based lookup;
the Elm client's local state always reflects current indices
because its event loop mutates atomically.

This isn't a bug — it's the contract. The wire is a log of
*what happened*, not *named entities over time*. Content-by-
content is how introspecting consumers resolve references.

## Tests

`replay_test.go` mirrors `tests/LynRummy/ReplayTest.elm`:
transition-per-action-type, turn-action no-ops, bad-reference
no-ops, sequenced actions, initial-state shape, ReplayActions
fold equivalence.

## Consumer endpoint

`GET /gopher/lynrummy-elm/sessions/<id>/state` — the server
response is literally `ReplayActions(actions_for_session)`.
Python player uses this.
